Interestingly enough, the example doesn't fail with `org.apache.commons.collections4.map.CaseInsensitiveMap`.

I tried the following without any changes from #2160 or #2167:

```java
  @Test
  void with_Commons_Collections_CaseInsensitiveMap() { // version 4.4
    Map<String, String> map = new CaseInsensitiveMap<>();
    map.put("TEST", "value");

    assertThat(map).containsKey("test");
    assertThat(map).contains(entry("test", "value"));

    assertThat(map).containsOnlyKeys("test");
    assertThat(map).containsOnly(entry("test", "value"));
  }

  @Test
  void with_Spring_LinkedCaseInsensitiveMap() { // version 5.3.5
    Map<String, String> map = new LinkedCaseInsensitiveMap<>();
    map.put("TEST", "value");

    assertThat(map).containsKey("test");
    assertThat(map).contains(entry("test", "value"));

    assertThat(map).containsOnlyKeys("test");
    assertThat(map).containsOnly(entry("test", "value"));
  }
```

and only the second test fails.

But if I change the first to:

```java
  @Test
  void with_Commons_Collections_CaseInsensitiveMap() {
    Map<String, String> map = new CaseInsensitiveMap<>();
    map.put("TEST", "value");

    // Capitalized key
    assertThat(map).containsOnlyKeys("Test");
    assertThat(map).containsOnly(entry("Test", "value"));
  }
```

then I get the failure.

@filiphr @joel-costigliola @scordio this issue also applies to sorted/navigable maps

```
    Map<String, String> actual = new TreeMap<>(String::compareToIgnoreCase);

    actual.put("Color", "green");
    actual.put("NAME", "Yoda");

    Assertions.assertThat(actual).containsExactly(
                                                  new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry<>("COLOR", "green"),
                                                  new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry<>("Name", "Yoda"));
```

That's a good one. I think that with the work @scordio has been doing this case is covered. This is another good test case.

btw @nach-o-man AssertJ already provides a factory method for creating `Map.Entry`. It is in `Assertions#entry`, a small hint in case you didn't know. If you statically import it the test then looks like:

```
 Map<String, String> actual = new TreeMap<>(String::compareToIgnoreCase);

    actual.put("Color", "green");
    actual.put("NAME", "Yoda");

    Assertions.assertThat(actual).containsExactly(
                                                  entry("COLOR", "green"),
                                                  entry("Name", "Yoda"));
```
